# Computational Mathematics Software Manual

## **Routine Name:** absoluteError 

**Description:** This is a routine for calculate the absolute difference between two doubles

**Input:**  The function takes as input two doubles.   

**Output:** It outputs a double representing the difference between the input values.  

**Code Example:**

```C++

#include <iostream>
#include <math.h>

using namespace std;


double absoluteError(double actual, double approximation){
    return abs(actual-approximation);
}

int main(){

    cout << absoluteError(0, .9) << endl;
    cout << absoluteError(1.1, 1.0) << endl;
    cout << absoluteError(5, 5.1) << endl;
}

```

**Results:** The output of running the main function is the following:

```C++
0.9
0.1
0.1

```
The above numbers represent the absolute error between the two input values of the function.  

